{"cursor":"27560","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematics, the 'matrix exponential' is a matrix function on square matrices\nanalogous to the ordinary exponential function. Abstractly, the matrix\nexponential gives the connection between a matrix Lie algebra and the\ncorresponding Lie group.\n\nLet X be an nÃn real or complex matrix. The exponential of X, denoted by\ne X or exp(X), is the nÃn matrix given by the power series\n\n: e^X = \\sum_{k=0}^\\infty{1 \\over k!}X^k.\n\nThe above series always converges, so the exponential of X is well-defined. Note\nthat if X is a 1Ã1 matrix the matrix exponential of X is a 1Ã1 matrix consisting\nof the ordinary exponential of the single element of X.\n","linknr":394,"url":"Matrix_exponential","recorded":1362899586,"links":23,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","linear_algebra"],"pdf":["http://www.cs.cornell.edu/cv/researchpdf/19ways+.pdf","http://www.cs.cornell.edu/cv/researchpdf/19ways+.pdf"],"categories":["Matrix theory","Lie groups","Exponentials"],"headings":["Properties","Computing the matrix exponential","Calculations","Applications","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/4/6/646c5b8224494c252ee793a064973715.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/1/e/51e8ef27d2e2a1dcae84b980b22851a5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/3/6/a369e879f2731c1bfcf5a2509ca342a3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/7/d/a7da39db88bdbe8e2a0b5314b13ef30b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/d/2/4d2fc206807af2a3891718bbef1c2dfc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/3/1/931b764ac15e121b861373c242b72d74.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/5/1/d51872a327c8a1c07115ccffb37bfe32.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/1/d/c1d9f50f86825a1a2302ec2449c17196.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/f/e/6feb8819d050d19649bd9fe13fb65645.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/a/7/3a7fc135d0755d8045ddd376ac9152be.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/8/5/c8556fe5f925a35089cd0d5e352224b3.png",